Across all models, predictive performance was modest. Using the cleaned dataset, the GLM achieved a test AUC of approximately 0.63, with TabPFN delivering a near-identical result. When applied to the raw dataset (containing many sparse categorical levels and ungrouped variables) both models again produced very similar AUC values, with no material advantage for TabPFN. These results suggest that in this setting, most of the predictive signal is already captured by a relatively simple additive structure.
One particular point of interest was how each model behaves across different decision thresholds. As lapses are a relatively rare event, the dataset is inherently imbalanced and so accuracy as a metric would be misleading (with high accuracy achievable simply by predicting non-lapse). Instead, metrics such as recall, precision and F1 score provide a more informative view. For both models, optimal F1 scores were achieved at relatively low probability cutoffs (around 0.10 - 0.15), reflecting the need to trade off false positives against missed lapses.
Interestingly, TabPFN’s ability to operate directly on the raw dataset did not translate into improved predictive power over the GLM. While the model handled sparse categories and mixed feature types without difficulty, its performance closely mirrored that of the GLM once basic actuarial data preparation had been applied. This finding is consistent with the exploratory analysis presented earlier: many of the strongest drivers of lapse in this dataset (such as policyholder age, payment frequency and policy tenure) exhibit smooth, monotonic effects that are well aligned with a logistic regression framework.
 
Conclusion
Having set out to explore if TabPFN can deliver tangible benefits over a traditional actuarial GLM, we find the answer is not always! Examining a realistic lapse-modelling context using the eudirectlapse dataset, we find little evidence that TabPFN materially outperforms a carefully specified logistic regression model, whether applied to cleaned or raw data. In this case, the GLM appears to capture most of the available predictive signal.
 
Does this mean that TabPFN is limited? Not necessarily so, rather our analysis highlights an important practical insight: when the underlying relationships are largely additive, monotonic and well understood, classical actuarial models remain highly competitive. The value of TabPFN may lie elsewhere, likely in settings with more complex interactions, smaller datasets, or where a quick answer without the need for extensive feature engineering is desirable. From an actuarial perspective, TabPFN’s most compelling contribution may therefore be workflow efficiency rather than outright predictive dominance. The ability to obtain reasonable predictions without extensive preprocessing, hyperparameter tuning or model selection is attractive, particularly in exploratory or time-constrained settings. The transparency, interpretability and regulatory familiarity of GLMs remain powerful advantages, although the integration of TabPFN with Shapley values may well come to challenge this.
 
In summary we have come to realise that the right method for the task is often dataset dependent. Old-fashioned data visualisation and exploration can be a helpful safeguard against the temptation to get carried away with complex methodologies. While using a sledgehammer to crack a nut can be tremendous fun, we should aim for thesimplest solution that fits the problem. Ultimately, our results reinforce a reassuring message for practitioners: while new modelling tools continue to expand our toolkit, there is still plenty of life in the old GLM yet!
